\n! # !! Name !! Term !! Record (W\u2013L)\n|-\n|1 || Norma Boetel || 1966\u201370 || 35\u20131\n|-\n|2 || Ruth Marske || 1970\u201372 || 32\u20134\n|-\n|3 || Norma Boetel || 1972\u201373 || 11\u20137\n|-\n|4 || Jenny Johnson || 1973\u201374 || 13\u20134\n|-\n|5 || Norma Boetel || 1974\u201376 || 33\u201311\n|-\n|6|| Cindy Davis || 1976\u201378 || 28\u201320\n|-\n|7|| Mary Ingram || 1978\u201384 || 72\u201384\n|-\n|8|| Nancy {{not a typo|Neiber}} || 1984\u20132000 || 301\u2013140\n|-\n|9|| [[Aaron Johnston (basketball)|Aaron Johnston]] || 2000\u2013present\u2020 || 441\u2013149\n|-\n|}\n<small>\u2020 [[Aaron Johnston (basketball)|Aaron Johnston]] took over for Nancy {{not a typo|Neiber}} during the last six games of the 1999-2000 season.</small>\n\n==Media coverage==\n\nAll home and road games are covered on the Jackrabbit Sports Network.  The broadcast range of the Jackrabbit Sports Network covers eight states ([[South Dakota]], [[Minnesota]], [[North Dakota]], [[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]], [[Missouri]], [[Kansas]], and [[Wyoming]]), and consists of the following stations:\n*[[WNAX (AM)|WNAX]] 570AM (Flagship Station)\n*[[KJJQ]] 910AM\n*[[KRKI]] 99.1FM\n*[[KGFX (AM)|KGFX]] 1060AM\n*[[KSDR (AM)|KSDR]] 1480AM\n\nThe team does not have an official television partner, but Jackrabbit games have been televised on Midco Sports Net, [[ESPN2]], [[ESPNU]], and local television networks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{South Dakota State Jackrabbits women's basketball navbox}}\n{{South Dakota State University}}\n{{Summit League women's basketball navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:South Dakota State Jackrabbits Women's Basketball}}\n[[Category:South Dakota State Jackrabbits women's basketball| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college basketball team|women=yes\n|name = South Dakota State Jackrabbits\n|current = 2019\u201320 South Dakota State Jackrabbits women's basketball team\n|logo = South Dakota State University logo.svg\n|logo_size = 150\n|university = South Dakota State University\n|conference = [[Summit League]]\n|location = [[Brookings, South Dakota]]\n|coach = [[Aaron Johnston (basketball)|Aaron Johnston]]\n|tenure = 21st\n|arena = [[Frost Arena]]\n|capacity = 6,500<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gojacks.com/downloads1/362394.pdf?ATCLID=3750178&SPSID=64556&SPID=7144&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=15000 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-02-19 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304000106/http://www.gojacks.com/downloads1/362394.pdf?ATCLID=3750178&SPSID=64556&SPID=7144&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=15000 |archive-date=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref>\n|nickname = [[South Dakota State Jackrabbits|Jackrabbits]]\n|h_body= 0033A0\n|h_pattern_b=_thinsidesonwhite\n|h_shorts= 0033A0\n|h_pattern_s=_blanksides2\n|a_body= 0033A0\n|a_pattern_b=_thingoldsides\n|a_shorts= 0033A0\n|a_pattern_s=_thingoldsides\n|NCAAchampion = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>2003  \n|NCAArunnerup = \n|NCAAfinalfour = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>2002, 2003\n|NCAAeliteeight = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>2002, 2003, 2004\n|NCAAsweetsixteen = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>1994, 1995, 2002, 2003, 2004<br/><small>[[NCAA Division I|Division I]]</small><br/>2019\n|NCAAsecondround = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>1988, 1994, 1995, 2002, 2003, 2004<br/><small>[[NCAA Division I|Division I]]</small><br/>2009, 2016, 2019\n|NCAAtourneys = <small>[[NCAA Division II|Division II]]</small><br/>1988, 1992, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1999, 2002, 2003, 2004<br/><small>[[NCAA Division I|Division I]]</small><br/>2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2018, 2019\n|conference_tournament = 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, 2016, 2018, 2019\n|conference_season = 2003, 2004 ([[North Central Conference|NCC]])<br/> 2008, 2009, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2019\n| AIAWtourneys = 1972\n}}\n\nThe '''South Dakota State Jackrabbits women's basketball''' team is part of the athletic program at [[South Dakota State University]] in [[Brookings, South Dakota]]. The NCAA Division I team is a member of [[The Summit League]].  The Jackrabbits head coach is Aaron Johnston.\n\n==History==\nSouth Dakota State began play in 1966. In the times they were in the AIAW, they won the State title 11 times from 1969 to 1982, including six straight from 1969 to 1975, including a Regional title in 1972. In their time in Division II, they made the [[NCAA Division II Women's Basketball Tournament]] in 1988, 1992, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1999, 2002, 2003, and 2004. They garnered a record of 18-8. In 2003, they won a [[NCAA Women's Division II Basketball Championship|NCAA Division II national title]] when they defeated [[Northern Kentucky Norse women's basketball|Northern Kentucky]] by a score of 65\u201350. They began play in Division I in 2004. Prior to joining the Division I Summit League, they were a member of the Division II [[North Central Conference]]. As of the end of the 2018-19 season, they have a 993-422 all-time record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gojacks.com/sports/2007/6/25/942527.aspx?path=wbball|title=SDSU Women's Basketball History|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/jackrabbitathletics/docs/2016-17_sdsu_wbb_media_guide|title=2016-17 South Dakota State Women's Basketball|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Jackrabbits played in the [[NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship]] in each of their first five years of eligibility, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2013. The also played in the NCAA D-I Basketball Championship in 2015, 2016, 2018 and 2019, making the Sweet Sixteen in 2019. The Jackrabbits played in the 2007, 2008, 2014, and 2017 Women's WNIT Tournaments. In their Division I history, the team has compiled four regular-season Summit League titles and seven Summit League postseason conference-tourney titles. The 2008\u20132009 team was ranked #14 in ESPN/USA Today Division I Coaches Poll en route to a 32\u20133 record and received large amounts of national media coverage. The 2018-2019 team was ranked as the #1 Mid-Major team and during the regular season was ranked in the top 25 overall for Division I.\n\n==Postseason appearances==\n===NCAA Division I Tournament results===\n\nThe Jackrabbits have appeared in nine [[NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Division I Tournaments]]. They achieved their highest ranking in 2019 with a 6 seed. Their record is 4\u20139.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=South Dakota State Jackrabbits |Year|Seed|Round|Opponent|Result}}\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2009 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2009]] \n| #7\n| First Round <br/> Second Round\n| #10 TCU <br/> #2 Baylor\n| '''W''' 90\u201355 <br/> L 58\u201360\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2010 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2010]] \n| #14\n| First Round\n| #3 Oklahoma\n| L 57\u201368\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2011 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2011]] \n| #15\n| First Round\n| #2 Xavier\n| L 56\u201372\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2012 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2012]] \n| #13\n| First Round\n| #4 Purdue\n| L 68\u201383\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2013 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2013]] \n| #13\n| First Round\n| #4 South Carolina\n| L 53\u201374\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2015 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2015]]\n| #14\n| First Round\n| #3 Oregon State\n| L 62\u201374\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2016 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2016]] \n| #12\n| First Round <br/> Second Round\n| #5 Miami <br/> #4 Stanford\n| '''W''' 74\u201371 <br/> L 65\u201366\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2018 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2018]] \n| #8\n| First Round \n| #9 Villanova \n| L 74\u201381 (OT)\n|- align=\"center\"\n| [[2019 NCAA Women's Division I Basketball Tournament|2019]]\n| #6\n| First Round <br/> Second Round <br/> Sweet Sixteen\n| #11 Quinnipiac <br/> #3 Syracuse <br/> #